During the on-state for one converter, the switch SW is closed. Therefore, the input voltage VS appears across the switched inductors. As a result, a change in the current ΔiL flows through the switched inductors during a time period Δt by the formula: ΔiL = (1/Leq1) VS Δt.ΔiL=(1/Leq1)VSΔt.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \Delta_{{{\text{iL}}}} = (1/{\text{L}}_{{{\text{eq}}1}} ){\text{V}}_{{\text{S}}} \Delta {\text{t}}{.} $$\end{document}where Leq1 is the equivalent inductance of the switched inductors during the on-state, and it is equal to L/2 as the two inductors are connected in parallel.

At the end of the on-state, the increase of iL is:ΔiL-on=(1/Leq1)∫0DTVinΔt=(2/L)VS(DT-0)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
